  "doc_id": "41067",
  "text": "The first neurocognitive studies have been performed in this area, all in the domain of anxiety, investigating neurocognitive changes due to this type of training [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ). It appears that training attention towards or away from fear stimuli (angry faces) modifies relationships between lateral prefrontal and posterior (fusiform face area) regions, as evidenced by the need to recruit lateral prefrontal cortex to overcome the trained bias [CITATION_3] . From the perspective developed above, this increased activity suggests reprocessing due to the fast but incorrect attentional response caused by training. In general agreement with this finding, parieto-occipital P2 potentials evoked by task-irrelevant threatening stimuli have been found to be reduced by attentional training in anxious individuals [CITATION_4] . This suggests an increase in the ability to disengage from, or to discontinue the reprocessing of, threatening information [CITATION_5] . In upcoming studies we will investigate whether similar changes are found as a function of re-training in the addiction domain.",
